label.value: normal meiotic spindle polarity

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which spindle microtubules are oriented normally, i.e. with minus ends at the spindle poles and plus ends at the midzone, during or both meiotic nuclear divisions.

definition.value: Consider also annotating to 'meiotic spindle pole body detached from nucleus' (FYPO:0006365).

label.value: normal protein localization to centromere

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the centromere of a chromosome is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to kinetochore during meiotic anaphase I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the kinetochore of a chromosome is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during anaphase of meiosis I.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein phosphorylation during mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint signaling

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a lower extent than normal during mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint signaling.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased duration of protein localization to spindle during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the duration of localization of a protein to the spindle is longer than normal during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to meiotic spindle midzone during meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the spindle midzone is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during the first meiotic nuclear division. The meiotic spindle midzone is the area in the center of the meiotic spindle where the spindle microtubules from opposite poles overlap.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: mitotic DNA re-replication in absence of mitotic spindle

value.value: A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell undergoes one or more rounds of rereplication of the entire genome without forming a mitotic spindle or undergoing cytokinesis.

label.value: nuclear division in absence of mitotic spindle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the nucleus divides into two or more fragments, each enclosed by nuclear envelope and containing a DNA mass, in a cell that does not form a mitotic spindle or undergo cytokinesis. In these cells, the nucleus does not elongate into a dumbbell shape, but instead the nuclear envelope takes on a ruffled aspect and then eventually pinches into two nuclear masses.

label.value: spindle pole body separation in absence of mitotic spindle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the spindle pole body (SPB) duplicates normally, and the SPBs separate, in a cell that does not form a mitotic spindle or undergo cytokinesis. The DNA and nucleus may go on to divide in the absence of a spindle, with each DNA mass associated with an SPB.

label.value: sister chromatid separation during nuclear fission

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which sister chromatids become physically detached in a cell that does not form a mitotic spindle or undergo cytokinesis. The DNA and nucleus may go on to divide in the absence of a spindle, with sister chromatids segregated to separate DNA masses.

label.value: centromere clustering at nuclear periphery during nuclear division in absence of mitotic spindle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which centromeres and kinetochores remain associated with the spindle pole body during nuclear division in a that does not form a mitotic spindle or undergo cytokinesis.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to spindle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic or meiotic spindle is abnormal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished protein localization to meiotic spindle pole during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to one or both poles of the meiotic spindle does not occur during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to spindle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic or meiotic spindle is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to meiotic spindle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the meiotic spindle is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to meiotic spindle pole during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to one or both poles of the meiotic spindle is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: sensitive to actin polymerization inhibitor

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to a substance that inhibits actin polymerization. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of an actin polymerization inhibitor that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: abnormal protein localization to lateral cell cortex

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the lateral cell cortex is abnormal.

label.value: abolished protein localization to lateral cell cortex, with protein mislocalized to cytoplasm, during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the lateral cell cortex is abolished, and the protein is present in the cytoplasm instead.

label.value: decreased protein localization to lateral cell cortex, with protein distributed in cell cortex, during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the lateral cortex of a cell is decreased, and some of the protein is detected distributed throughout the cell cortex. There may be little or no protein detected at the medial cortex.

label.value: abolished plasma membrane flow from cell pole to lateral region

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which bulk plasma membrane flow from the cell poles to lateral regions does not occur.

label.value: abnormal exocytosis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which exocytosis is abnormal. Exocytosis is the release of intracellular molecules (e.g. hormones, matrix proteins) contained within a membrane-bounded vesicle by fusion of the vesicle with the plasma membrane of a cell. A phenotype may affect exocytosis of all cargoes, or of specific cargo such as a particular protein.

label.value: decreased exocytosis at shmoo tip

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which exocytosis occurs to a lower extent than normal at the shmoo tip.

label.value: normal protein localization to actin fusion focus

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the actin fusion focus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased plasma membrane waviness at shmoo tip

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the plasma membrane is smoother than normal at the shmoo tip. Normally, the plasma membrane of one of a pair of mating cells is slack shmoo tip, forming waves instead of a smooth arc.

label.value: normal regulation of translation in response to chemical

value.value: A gene expression phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which regulation of translation in response to a chemical stimulus is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased protein degradation during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of protein degradation is decreased during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate. Protein degradation, also known as protein catabolism, is any metabolic process that results in the destruction of the native, active configuration of a protein, with or without the hydrolysis of peptide bonds.

label.value: abolished protein degradation during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein degradation does not occur during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate. Protein degradation, also known as protein catabolism, is any metabolic process that results in the destruction of the native, active configuration of a protein, with or without the hydrolysis of peptide bonds.

label.value: normal protein degradation during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein degradation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate. Protein degradation, also known as protein catabolism, is any metabolic process that results in the destruction of the native, active configuration of a protein, with or without the hydrolysis of peptide bonds.

label.value: increased duration of histone H2A phosphorylation during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the duration of  histone H2A phosphorylation is longer than normal during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate. All histone H2A phosphorylation may be affected, or phosphorylation of specific sites on histone H2A may be affected.

label.value: normal protein kinase activity during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein kinase activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate.

label.value: decreased cleavage-dependent termination of RNA polymerase II transcription

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cleavage-dependent termination of transcription by RNA polymerase II is abnormal. In cleavage-dependent termination, co-transcriptional secondary structure-dependent endonucleolytic cleavage triggers RNA polymerase II transcription termination; transcripts are not polyadenylated, and are subsequently rapidly degraded in the nucleus. Termination of all transcripts, or a subset of transcripts, may be affected.

label.value: abolished Lsm2-8 complex binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which Lms2-8 complex binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant does not occur. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: decreased Lsm2-8 complex binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of Lms2-8 complex binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: abolished histone H3-K9 dimethylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which dimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 does not occur.

label.value: normal protein localization to kinetochore during mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint signaling

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the kinetochore of a chromosome is normal during mitotic spindle assembly checkpoint signaling.

label.value: decreased spatial extent of mating-type region heterochromatin assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which heterochromatin is assembled over a smaller portion of the mating-type region than normal.
increased histone turnover at subtelomeric heterochromatin

http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboI.value: increased histone exchange at subtelomeric heterochromatin

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which histone exchange at subtelomeric heterochromatin is increased. Histone exchange is replacement, within chromatin, of resident histones or histone subunits with alternative, sometimes variant, histones or subunits.

label.value: normal protein dephosphorylation during mitotic exit

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which protein dephosphorylation is normal during mitotic exit (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Protein dephosphorylation is the removal of a phosphate group from a protein amino acid.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased histone H2B-K119 ubiquitination at subtelomeric heterochromatin

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which ubiquitination of lysine at position 119 of histone H2B is increased at subtelomeric heterochromatin. Lysine 119 corresponds to the conserved C-terminal lysine of H2B.

label.value: increased histone H2B-K119 ubiquitination at pericentromeric heterochromatin

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which ubiquitination of lysine at position 119 of histone H2B is increased at pericentromeric heterochromatin. Lysine 119 corresponds to the conserved C-terminal lysine of H2B.

label.value: increased protein phosphorylation during mitotic exit

definition.value: A cellular process during mitosis in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a greater extent than normal during mitotic exit.

label.value: decreased actomyosin contractile ring actin filament length

value.value: A cytokinesis phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the length of actin filaments in the contractile ring is shorter than normal.

label.value: increased rate of protein localization to actomyosin contractile ring

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, localization of a protein to the actomyosin contractile ring is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased number of R-loops

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA-DNA hybrid molecules is greater than normal.

label.value: normal onset of cytokinesis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic cytokinesis begins at the same time as normal.

label.value: cell lysis during mitotic interphase

value.value: An inviable phenotype in which a cell lyses during mitotic interphase, i.e. the plasma membrane ruptures and cytoplasm is lost. Note that in fission yeast cell lysis, the integrity of the cell wall is also compromised.

label.value: abnormal glucan synthesis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which glucan biosynthesis is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal beta-glucan synthesis

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which beta-glucan biosynthesis is abnormal.

label.value: increased cell population growth rate during amino acid starvation

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a cell population in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle grows at a faster rate than normal during amino acid starvation.
